commentary: Southee to Taylor, FOUR runs wait, wait, what's that? Hope the people at Pepsi are watching. This is not the Sehwag Upar Cut. it is not the Dilshan Pallu scoop. Our man, Venkat Raghav names it the 'Perpendicular cut'. This is what happened: Brendan saw a short ball, thought he had room to play the upper cut, and arched back, while angling the bat face. And then he noticed it coming in sharply, cramping him for room. What does Brendan do? He arches further back, and the ball is actually where his head was when he took stance. He then plays the upper cut. And gets it down to fine leg. Go figure!

commentary: Southee to Taibu, OUT Southee probably doesn't have to wait long for redemption. Zimbabwe have refered an lbw appeal that was upheld. commentary: Vettori to Chigumbura, OUT Captain gets captain first ball. Or has he? Elton reviews a potentially controversial lbw decision. Tossed up on middle, back of a length and it straightens. Here's the catch - Elton has charged a mile out of his crease. Ok, may be not a mile, but 2.5 metres for sure. The replays say it pitched on the line of the stumps, hit in front of middle as Elton misses the chip to the leg side. The potentially questionable predictive powers of Hawk-Eye (since he was well out of the crease) say it was hitting leg stump. It is back to umpire Erasmus, and he, like Billy Bowden the other day, sticks to his decision. Only, this time, it is out.

commentary: Lamb to Guptill, no run whoa, that must have been close. Will Zimbabwe refer it? Umpire Aleem Dar has turned down the lbw appeal, and they are reviewing it. Tossed up outside off and turning into the batsman, Guptill tries to flick from the line of off stump, without getting to the pitch. It turned in sharply and hit him in front of middle. No inside edge there. However, Hawk-Eye says that was going well down the leg side. Guptill is safe.

commentary: Chigumbura to Guptill, no run back of a length, and driven solidly back down the track by Guptill. Hits the stumps at the bowler's end, but Elton did not get a finger on it. Brendon might have been out if he had.

commentary: Panyangara to BB McCullum, SIX runs the Amdavadi vendors sitting outside the stadium, watch out. A projectile may be headed your way. Length ball from Tinashe on off stump, certainly not the worst he's bowled today. Brendon flexes those tattooed biceps as he whacks the leather off the ball and sends it almost into orbit. It lands in the midwicket stands. Soon one may land beyond the stands.

commentary: Panyangara to Guptill, FOUR runs Guptill has finished it off in style. The Kiwis have tamed the Eagles today in Ahmedabad. Emphatically. Tinashe delivers a friendly length ball on the pads and Guptill gets under it and bashes on the up, almost all the way. Lands a foot inside the long on fence and runs over the ropes. All over.
